## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests. 0 real verifications.** This is a systematic **coverage-touching** pattern — every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called to inflate code-coverage metrics, but almost nothing is actually verified. This explains why you hit 95% coverage yet keep finding production bugs.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | 7 |
| High | 1 |
| Medium | 1 |
| Low | 1 |

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic — all 10 tests)

The entire test class is a coverage-touching suite. Methods are called in roughly declaration order with no meaningful assertions. This is the root cause of your production bugs.

#### 2. No Assertions — 5 tests verify absolutely nothing

These tests call a method and return. If the method silently corrupts data, the test still passes green.

| Test | Line | What's untested |
|------|------|-----------------|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17 | Never checks the product was actually persisted |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 33 | Never checks the price actually changed |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 39 | Never checks the product was actually removed |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 64 | Never checks the returned count |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 69 | Never checks prices were reduced |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 85 | Never checks products were imported |

**Fix for `AddProduct_Works` (line 17):**
```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER — verifies the product is retrievable with correct data
var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
```

**Fix for `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 33):**
```csharp
// BEFORE
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// AFTER
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
```

**Fix for `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69):**
```csharp
// BEFORE
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

// AFTER
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
var widget = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
var gadget = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002");
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, widget?.Price);   // 9.99 * 0.90
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, gadget?.Price);  // 19.99 * 0.90
```

#### 3. Trivial `Assert.IsNotNull` Masquerading as Verification — 3 tests

`GetProduct_Works` (line 25), `SearchProducts_Works` (line 46), `GetAllProducts_Works` (line 55), and `ExportToCsv_Works` (line 78) assert only `IsNotNull`. These methods will *never* return null for a valid SKU/non-empty store, so the assertion is always-true in practice. None verify the **content** of the result.

**Fix for `SearchProducts_Works` (line 46):**
```csharp
// BEFORE — IsNotNull is always true (Search returns List, never null)
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.IsNotNull(results);

// AFTER — verifies correct filtering
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.AreEqual(1, results.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", results[0].Sku);
```

**Fix for `GetAllProducts_Works` (line 55):**
```csharp
// BEFORE
var all = _catalog.GetAll();
Assert.IsNotNull(all);

// AFTER
var all = _catalog.GetAll();
Assert.AreEqual(1, all.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", all[0].Sku);
```

